The backend layer is the bridge between block_csr.hpp, the packed storage,
and the apply kernels for SpMV/SpMM and their adjoints.

Boundary rules:
1. Storage backends own persistent matrix storage, page slicing metadata,
   apply plans, vendor cache lifetime, and invalidation when storage moves or
   changes.
2. Vendor helper headers build and destroy persistent descriptors/handles from
   backend-owned slices. They may know MKL/AOCL handle types, index-base
   quirks, and cache variants, but not launch policy.
3. Kernel headers own per-call execution policy: native versus vendor
   dispatch, threading configuration, OpenMP division, and fallback behavior.
